metadata.name: Faux #255
metadata.description:
This project is borne out of my longstanding fascination with brushwork, and the intricate textures that can be created with a brush, some paint and a canvas. Brush strokes are simulated using many overlapping lines and given texture and depth using a custom shader. Another important aspect of this work, is the composite forms that are created by the brush strokes, which are my attempt to emulate the emphatic energy of many abstract painters that have come before me. Color palettes are named after common paint colors, based on the background color used for the palette.

Those who collect during the first tier of the Dutch Auction can claim a signed print. They will be printed on A3 Hahnemuhle Photo Rag, and shipped to the collector free of charge. More details on how to claim a print and specify the necessary shipping information will be provided via the artists twitter (@landlinesart1).

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: MOMENT #172
metadata.description:
An endless row of them making up each life. Some poignant, some inspiring, some grievous, some affirming - but most of them a tad boring, a bit generic, almost forgettable like bland fabric. How can a life constructed from such mundanity count for anything? Maybe thanks to the last one, the one that stitches them all together, like a punchline to an absurdist joke.

Generative art written in JavaScript + Canvas with a little bit of help from p5.js.

A zigzag is a pattern made up of small corners at variable angles, though constant within the zigzag, tracing a path between two parallel lines; it can be described as both jagged and fairly regular.
In geometry, this pattern is described as a skew apeirogon. From the point of view of symmetry, a regular zigzag can be generated from a simple motif like a line segment by repeated application of a glide reflection.

Another name for the pattern is "Herringbone" FYI ü§ì

There's a chance no lines are shown at all, this is intentional, as I love "bugs" ü™≤

metadata.name: citylines #121
metadata.description: For this project, I decided to learn how to code up isometric buildings using just lines, custome shapes, and fills. Pretty fun actually. In the process, some interesting distributions of buildings kept popping up - like buildings on the outer edges only for example. So I made them explicit features (City Splits). The variations you can expect are colors, city splits (trio is my favorite!), building pattern type (i love lines :)), max building height, and # of pyramids. I hope you get some amazing outputs! Enjoy :)

metadata.name: Glomularus Unleashed #28
metadata.description:
'Glomularus Unleashed' is a limited edition drop, in appreciation of passionate and generous supporters. 

The project continues my explorations in artificial life, moving Glomularus outside of the computational void and into the world at large. 'Glomularus Unleashed' includes 23 unique immersive environments. 



Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
1-9: add acceleration
-, +: reduce | increase V-eco sphere radius
f, g: reduce | increase fog
p: screen capture

Tip:
To decrease creature acceleration, reduce V-eco sphere radius

Note:
Please post your favorite 'Glomularus Unleashed' screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node
